# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: black-pudding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:black-pudding/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] A **3-in-1**, **trio** or **three-in-one** is a fast-food dish consisting of chips, boiled rice (or egg fried rice), and curry sauce served in a single foil tray or plastic container.
[src:black-pudding/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] It became popular in Ireland as a dish from chip shops and Chinese restaurants in the early twenty-first century.
[src:black-pudding/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] It developed a cult following in the 2010s, and media outlets debated the merits of it compared to a spice bag, which became popular around the same time.
[src:black-pudding/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] Related dishes (four-, five-in one) contain additional ingredients such as chicken balls, or chicken or beef pieces.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] At the time, many ingredients were scarcely obtainable, but the book was quickly recognised as serious, and within a few years it profoundly changed English cooking and eating habits.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Returning to postwar England, still with food rationing, after years living in the Mediterranean with its wealth of fresh ingredients, Elizabeth David found life grey and daunting.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The food was terrible: "There was flour and water soup seasoned solely with pepper; bread and gristle rissoles; dehydrated onions and carrots; corned beef toad in the hole.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Partly to earn some money, and partly from an "agonized craving for the sun", David began writing articles on Mediterranean cookery.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Her first efforts were published in 1949 in the British edition of *Harper's Bazaar*.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] From the outset, David refused to sell the copyright of her articles, and so she was able to collect and edit them for publication in book form.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Even before all the articles had been published, she had assembled them into a typescript volume and submitted it to a series of publishers, all of whom turned it down.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] One of them explained that a collection of unconnected recipes needed linking text.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] David took this advice, but, conscious of her inexperience as a writer, she kept her own prose short and quoted extensively from established authors whose views on the Mediterranean might carry more weight.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] In the published volume, the sections are linked by substantial extracts from works by writers including Norman Douglas, Lawrence Durrell, Gertrude Stein, D.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Lawrence, Osbert Sitwell, Compton Mackenzie, Arnold Bennett, Henry James and Théophile Gautier.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] She submitted the revised typescript to John Lehmann, a publisher more associated with poetry than cookery, but he accepted it, agreeing to an advance payment of £100.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] *A Book of Mediterranean Food* was published in 1950.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Lehmann had suggested it be named "The Blue Train Cookery Book", since he supposed that the romance of Mediterranean countries was to be found in the exciting train journeys to reach them.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The book appeared when food rationing imposed during the Second World War remained fully in force in Britain.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The historian of food Panikos Panayi argues that with *A Book of Mediterranean Food*, David profoundly changed English cooking.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Lehmann commissioned a coloured dust-jacket painting and black and white internal illustrations from his friend the artist John Minton.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Writers including Cyril Ray and John Arlott commented that Minton's drawings added to the attractions of the book.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] David, a woman of strong opinions, thought good illustration important.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Minton provided 15 decorations to give a feeling of the Mediterranean, rather than simple illustrations of dishes from David's recipes.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] For example, his port scene shows a sailor drinking and conversing with a young woman beside a table laden with food; in the background is a street restaurant and boats in a harbour.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Although David did not like Minton's black and white drawings, she described his jacket design as "stunning".
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The chapters cover in turn: soups; eggs and luncheon dishes; fish; meat; substantial dishes; poultry and game; vegetables; cold food and salads; sweets; jams, chutneys and preserves; and sauces.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The soup chapter sets the pattern for the book, with short, simple recipes, such as soup of haricot beans – two brief paragraphs – interspersed with long, complex ones like that for Mediterranean fish soup, which covers three pages.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The eggs and luncheon dish section likewise balances the concise and simple such as *ratatouille aux oeufs* against the detailed and discursive three-page consideration of omelettes.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The meat section begins with recipes for veal, generally unfamiliar at English tables in 1950.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] David also gives recipes for kid and boar.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Mutton, by contrast, was more often served then than in more recent decades, and David gives four recipes for it, one of them disguising the flavour to taste like venison by long marinating and highly seasoned saucing.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The "substantial dishes" chapter discusses and illustrates the merits of risotto and paella, and deals with polenta and spaghetti – both less familiar in Britain then than now – and goes on to describe cassoulet.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The next chapter, on poultry and game, begins with recipes for cooking chicken and duck, and goes on to partridge – both *à la provençale* and in Greek style – quail and pigeons, concluding with snipe cooked *en papillote* with mushrooms.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The Mediterranean theme of the book is emphasised in the section on vegetables, in which there are five aubergine recipes and only one potato dish (*pommes Anna*).
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Dishes from Greece and North Africa are included along with typical southern French standards such as *tomates provençales*.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The occasional non-Mediterranean dish is included, including *cèpes à la bordelaise* fried in olive oil with parsley and garlic.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The cold food and salads chapter gives instructions for three dishes of cold chicken, several traditional pâtés and terrines, and another non-Mediterranean recipe, the traditional Easter dish from Burgundy, *jambon persillé de Bourgogne*.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] David adds to this section suggestions for hors d'oeuvres, including Greek dishes then unfamiliar in Britain including dolmádes and taramá, as well as traditional French recipes such as *sardines marinées à la niçoise*.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] In the section on sweets, David comments that throughout the Mediterranean countries, the more complicated sweets are very often bought from pâtisseries; the few recipes she gives are for simple, traditional sweets made at home, such as *torrijas* (also called *pain perdu*) and cold orange soufflé.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The jams, chutneys and preserves section includes preserved melon alongside more familiar fruits such as pears and plums.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] In the final chapter, on sauces, David includes classics like béchamel, béarnaise, hollandaise and mayonnaise (which, she advises, "stir steadily but not like a maniac").
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] To these she adds Turkish, Greek, Italian and Egyptian sauces, the majority of them intended to go with Mediterranean fish dishes.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Rachel Cooke, writing in *The Guardian*, quotes the chef Simon Hopkinson, who knew David in the 1980s, as believing that David's "powerful effect .. on British palates .. was as much a question of timing as anything else".
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Melanie McDonagh, writing in *The Telegraph*, states that with *A Book of Mediterranean Food*, David "introduced the Brits to the cooking of Greece, Italy and Provence in 1950 after her return from Greece, via Egypt and India".
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] She comments that the cookery writer Jane Grigson, a "devotee", said "Basil was no more than the name of bachelor uncles, courgette was printed in italics as an alien word, and few of us knew how to eat spaghetti ...
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Dissenting from the general acclaim, Tom Norrington-Davies, also writing in *The Telegraph*, argues that the book "reached only a very small section of the population", but at once qualifies this, stating that these readers were "undergoing a dramatic upheaval.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Educated, moderately wealthy women suddenly found themselves in their kitchens without servants".
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] He cites Jane Grigson's observation, introducing a collection of David's writing, that "Elizabeth didn't so much restore [middle-class women's] confidence in cooking as invent it".
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Joe Moran, writing in the *Financial Times*, describes the genesis of the book as a "defining moment".
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] It was when, "stranded by a blizzard" in a hotel in Ross-on-Wye whose restaurant served meals so dismal that they seemed to her to be "produced with a kind of bleak triumph which amounted almost to a hatred of humanity and humanity’s needs", David felt her famous "agonised craving for the sun".
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Furious at the joyless food, she started to draft the "sensuous descriptions" of Mediterranean food that led to *A Book of Mediterranean Food*.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Marian Burros, writing in *The New York Times*, comments that David first showed "her importance" with the book.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] "The ration-weary English could barely buy enough to eat but they were enchanted by her descriptions of meals that included eggs, butter, seafood, tomatoes, olives, apricots, ingredients that were difficult, or impossible, to obtain.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] Foods that are taken for granted today in England – garlic, olive oil, Parmigiano Reggiano – were unknown and generally viewed with suspicion before Mrs.
[src:black-pudding/a-book-of-mediterranean-food] The book has appeared in the following editions since 1950, including translations into Danish and Chinese.
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] The book contains early recipes for plum (Christmas) pudding and suet pudding, and the first printed recipe for orange marmalade (without chunks).
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] Mary Kettilby indicated her intended audience with the book's full title, *A Collection of above Three Hundred Receipts in Cookery, Physick and Surgery; For the Use of all Good Wives, Tender Mothers, and Careful Nurses*.
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] The book was actually a collective effort: the preface states that "a Number of very Curious and Delicate House-wives Clubb'd to furnish out this Collection".
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] The book contains an early recipe for suet pudding, and the first printed recipe for orange marmalade, though without the chunks typically used now.
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] The book is divided into chapters for food and chapters for remedies.
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] Apart from the Preface, there is no introduction of any sort: the recipes follow immediately after the chapter headings.
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] The book is clearly divided into chapters of recipes for food and for remedies, but within the chapters there is no definite structure.
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] For example, the first chapter begins with six recipes for soups, followed by recipes for collared beef, "French-Cutlets", collared mutton, stewed pigeons, broiled pigeons, dressed turbot, and then patties "for a Dish of Fish".
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] While some logic may be discerned in this ordering, readers need to refer to the index to locate any particular dish.
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] The recipes are given either as goals, as "To make Hogs-Puddings", or as titles, sometimes with descriptions, as "A very good Tansy".
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] Quantities are given in whichever units are convenient, as "a Gallon of grated Bread", "three Pounds of Currants", or "nine Eggs".
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] Often, quantities rely on the cook's judgement, as "as much Sugar as will make it very sweet".
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] Temperatures and timings are given when necessary, as "a cool Oven: Half an Hour bakes it." There are no lists of ingredients.
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] No additions were made to the 3rd, or 4th editions.
[src:black-pudding/a-collection-of-above-three-hundred-receipts-in-cookery-physick-and-surgery] Mary Ellen Snodgrass comments that the *Collection* was "for ordinary housewives", in "parallel to court cookbooks".
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The book is divided into 15 chapters, forming a strict chronological sequence of periods such as "the Georgian age", from around 1150 to around 2000.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The chapters describe the society of each time, often starting with the monarch and rich food and drink, and proceeding down to ordinary people and the common foods of the period.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The narrative freely combine outlines of the historical context, descriptions of recipes, stories about significant figures, and personal anecdotes.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] For example, "The Medieval Larder" has an extensive section on the "medieval pig", leading into a description of Dickson Wright's own childhood memories of helping to kill her father's pigs and making black pudding, chitterlings and sausages, as well as having hams and bacon smoked.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Each chapter is opened with a monochrome illustration from its period, with a detailed caption.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] There are 32 pages of colour plates illustrating famous cookery writers such as Robert May and stages of English cuisine such as "The 1950s kitchen".
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The book begins with a short introduction, in which Dickson Wright states that her "great passions" include food and history, so that she "always knew" she would come to write the book.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] She adds that another passion is field sports, "providing food and controlling pests and vermin", and that this runs like a "silver thread" through the book.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Dickson Wright begins around 1150 in the reign of King Henry II and Eleanor of Aquitaine, a time of relative peace and wealth.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The diet she describes included rabbit, deer, carp farmed in ponds, eels, salmon, poultry, sheep, cattle, cheese, pigs, bread, onions, parsnips, carrots, and beans, washed down with wine and beer.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Spices such as pepper, cinnamon, and ginger were costly, and not used to try to make rotten meat acceptable; Dickson Wright suggests they more likely masked the salt used to preserve food.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The 14th century *The Forme of Cury* often uses sugar alongside spices.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Recipes were complex; many dishes were served in pastry.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Each kind of meat was served with spices thought appropriate to it: for example, venison was eaten with sugar and cinnamon.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Dickson Wright describes in detail the diet and lifestyle of the Tudor Kings; under the influence of Catherine of Aragon, Henry VIII drank Spanish sherry, imported oranges, and planted salad gardens.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Enormous confections were made of marzipan.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Commoners too might eat sea and freshwater fish, or beef, though bacon, according to Andrew Boorde in 1542 was "good for carters and plowmen".
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] With the separation of the Church of England from the Church of Rome, religious fasting was reduced, and the fasting rules were relaxed in the time of Elizabeth I, so that eggs, cheese, and milk were allowed even on fast days.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Pastry developed from 'coffin' cases meant only to hold the food inside during cooking and serving; now pies and pasties of all kinds were available to travellers.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Milk and cream were used in desserts such as junkets and syllabubs.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] A treat might consist of buns made with eggs, raisins, and spices.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] In 1604, Elinor Fettiplace compiled a *Receipt Book*; she had married into an ancient aristocratic family – a Fettiplace fought at the Battle of Hastings in 1066; at least 20 people ate at her table every day.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] She lists several recipes for bitter Seville oranges.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Food is strongly seasonal; she pickles buds, vegetables, and fruits in season, and makes a spiced fruit cake for 100 people for a harvest or other feast.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] My Lord of Devonshire's Pudding is made of sliced white bread, dates, raisins, marrow or butter, cream, eggs, cinnamon, nutmeg, and sugar—a recipe that Dickson Wright specially likes.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] James I brought a new approach to English food in the Stuart era, introducing Scottish customs of boiling puddings in a cloth, cold-smoking fish, and baking biscuits such as shortbread.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Gervase Markham's 1615 *The English Huswife* calls for ingredients as varied as asparagus, capers, olives, lemons, and spinach.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Robert May's 1660 *The Accomplisht Cook* is based on his time in Paris, followed by being cook to the Grocer's Company and to the Star Chamber, providing elaborate feasts.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] He gives instructions for fattening up wild birds like godwits by force-feeding.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] He offers multiple recipes for sturgeon, at that time common in England's rivers.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The East India Company increased foreign trade in the 17th century, bringing spices, pepper, cloves, mace, nutmeg, and tea from the East.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Meanwhile, bananas appeared from Bermuda.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The Duke of York told the diarist Samuel Pepys that English seamen ate only "peas, pork, and boiled beef".
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The adventurer Sir Kenelm Digby, alongside many activities at King James's court, in Italy, and in Spain, wrote a 1669 cookery book, *The Closet of the Eminently Learned Sir Kenelme Digbie Knight Opened*.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Many of the recipes are attributed to aristocratic connections; his *Pan Cotto* is "as the Cardinals use in Rome".
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] King James II's coronation banquet in 1685 presented some "1,500 dishes ranging from puffins to pistachio creams" in Westminster Hall.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Gin, at first imported from Holland to accompany William of Orange's Glorious Revolution of 1688, was soon widely distilled; the resultant heavy drinking led to the 1736 Gin Act.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] John Evelyn praised salads in his "pompous and verbose" 1699 book *Aceteria: A Discourse of Sallets*.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The slave trade brought molasses, rum, and sugar, and black domestic servants to England.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Roasting and baking became less laborious with Georgian era innovations in fireplace and oven design, approaching a kitchen range; the poor prepared their pies and took them to the bakery to be cooked.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Josiah Wedgwood made fine earthenware dinner services for George III and the middle class.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Teapots diversified; Thomas Twining opened London's first tea-shop for ladies in 1717.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] In Dundee, James Keiller made marmalade from bitter Seville oranges.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Parson James Woodforde described sumptuous Georgian meals in his country parish.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The 18th century, with a literate audience, saw the birth of English cookery books for the general public: some 300 appeared in the century.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Hannah Glasse's *The Art of Cookery Made Plain and Easy* came out in 1746 and went through 17 editions by 1800.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Dickson Wright comments that the text is clear and simple, and the recipes, "a delight to follow", always work.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Glasse introduces recipes for curry, and for ice cream.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] In the 19th century, Marie-Antoine Carême, who had worked for the Czar of Russia, introduced the modern system of separate soup, fish, meat, and dessert courses *à la russe*.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Alexis Soyer introduced elegant and complex French cuisine for the wealthy, and catered for the 1851 Great Exhibition, feeding 1000 people a day.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Charles Dickens's 1843 *A Christmas Carol* describes a recognisably modern Christmas dinner with goose or turkey, Christmas pudding, oranges, chestnuts, and punch.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Soyer set up soup kitchens in Dublin during the Great Famine of Ireland, and improved hospital catering with Florence Nightingale in the Crimean War.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Street food in Victorian England grew to include fish and chips, tripe, whelks, and pea soup.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Tea became cheap, joining white bread in the diet of the poor, who suffered widely from rickets, caused by vitamin D deficiency.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] New foods such as mangoes, pineapples, and rhubarb became available to the middle classes.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Curry arrived from British India, along with Indian restaurants.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Dickson Wright characterises the Edwardian era with the overindulged "Tum Tum", alias King Edward VII, who enjoyed sailing, horses, food, and mistresses.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] She explains Edwardian country house weekends, with soup, game pies, jellies, trifles, shooting, and bed-hopping.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Richard D'Oyly Carte staged operettas and founded the Savoy Hotel in 1889, introducing the rich to *haute cuisine*, cooked simply.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Ironically, the population was healthier than ever before, as rationing provided enough for the poorest.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Postwar, Fanny Cradock and her husband Johnnie presented cookery as television entertainment.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] After the war, many suggestions for a "perfect meal" were made, varying wildly from pizza to curry, chow mein or roast beef and Yorkshire pudding.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The 1970s favoured prawn cocktail, cheese fondue, and Black Forest gateau; the 1990s "embraced sushi".
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Cookery writers from Elizabeth David to Delia Smith encouraged people to enjoy simple, well-cooked ingredients.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Henrietta Green championed local produce and farmers' markets.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Several reviewers broadly agreed that *A History of English Food* was informative, witty, and entertaining, though others found it unsystematic and snobbish.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] It was described by Christopher Hirst in *The Independent* as "surely destined for classic status".
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The reviewer remarked Dickson Wright's mention of badger hams in the West Country pubs of her childhood, and the nine sorts of tripe in Dewsbury market, "including penis and udder".
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Shilling finds this "an impressive tour" from a well-stocked mind.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] She describes Dickson Wright's approach as "a firmly chronological line across the landscape of culinary history, pausing at intervals to examine objects of interest." She agrees that the book is "opinionated and wildly idiosyncratic", in the tradition of W.N.W.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Fowler's "gin-soaked" *Countryman's Cooking* and Rupert Croft-Cooke's *English Cooking: A New Approach*.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] The book gives, Shilling asserts, a "glorious" impression of English cuisine's long and continuous development since the Middle Ages.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Fay Maschler, writing in *The Spectator*, calls the book a "less stringent, more capricious, generously illustrated account", giving the reader "a magical sense of almost having been there".
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] For her, the book works because of Dickson Wright's evident enthusiasm for food and farming, especially animals.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Rachel Cooke, reviewing *A History of English Food* for *The Guardian*, writes that she feels "pretty cross.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] All of the information in this book can be found elsewhere, and much better done, too." She compares the book unfavourably with Kate Colquhoun's 2008 *Taste: The Story of Britain Through Its Cooking* and Dorothy Hartley's 1954 "classic" *Food in England*.
[src:black-pudding/a-history-of-english-food] Cooke argues that Dickson Wright is "as particular as she is greedy", and "gruesomely snobbish", out of touch with "other people", preferring therefore the overindulgent Georgians who could afford a suitable retinue of servants.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] Mrs Rundell has been called "the original domestic goddess" and her book "a publishing sensation" and "the most famous cookery book of its time".
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] It ran to over 67 editions; the 1865 edition had grown to 644 pages, and earned two thousand guineas.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] The first edition of 1806 was a short collection of Rundell's recipes published by John Murray.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] It went through dozens of editions, both legitimate and pirated, in both Britain and the United States, where the first edition was published in 1807.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] The frontispiece typically credited the authorship to "A Lady".
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] Later editions continued for some forty years after Rundell's death.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] Emma Roberts edited the 64th edition, adding some recipes of her own.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] Sales of *A New System of Domestic Cookery* helped to found the John Murray publishing empire.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] Sales in Britain were over 245,000; worldwide, over 500,000; the book stayed in print until the 1880s.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] When Rundell and Murray fell out, she approached a rival publisher, Longman's, leading to a legal battle.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] The 1865 edition is divided into 35 chapters over 644 pages.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] The table of contents lists each recipe under its chapter heading.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] There is a set of tables of weights, measures, wages and taxes before the main text.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] In contrast to the relative disorder of English eighteenth century cookery books such as Eliza Smith's *The Compleat Housewife* (1727) or Elizabeth Raffald's *The Experienced English Housekeeper* (1769), Rundell's text is strictly ordered and neatly subdivided.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] The recipes are written as direct instructions.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] Quantities, if given, are incorporated in the text.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] Basic skills like making pastry are explained separately, and then not mentioned in recipes.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] Under "Pastry", Rundell gives directions for "Rich Puff Paste", "A less rich Paste", and "Crust for Venison Pasty", with variations such as "Raised Crusts for Custards or Fruit".
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] Advice is given on choosing the best supplies in the market.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] The review concluded that "though we have no respect for Mrs.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] Rundell received from her publisher, Mr.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] Severin Carrell, writing in *The Guardian*, calls Rundell "the original domestic goddess" and her book "a publishing sensation" of the early nineteenth century, as it sold "half a million copies and conquered America", as well as helping to found the John Murray publishing empire.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] For all that, Carrell notes, both "the most famous cookery book of its time" and Rundell herself vanished into obscurity.
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] Elizabeth Grice, writing in *The Daily Telegraph*, similarly calls Rundell "a Victorian domestic goddess", though without "Nigella's sexual frisson, or Delia's uncomplicated kitchen manners".
[src:black-pudding/a-new-system-of-domestic-cookery] There have been over 67 editions, success leading to constant revision and extension: the first edition had 344 pages, while the 1865 edition runs to 644 pages including the index.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] The **Abernethy biscuit** is a type of "digestive biscuit", a baked good originally designed to be eaten as a support to proper digestion.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] The Abernethy biscuit was invented by surgeon John Abernethy in the 18th century as a digestive improver.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] Abernethy believed that most diseases were due to disorders in digestion.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] The Abernethy biscuit was originally designed to be eaten as a support to proper digestion.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] In creating his biscuit, Abernethy was following a trend of other medical practitioners including English William Oliver of Bath, Somerset, inventor of the Bath Oliver; and the American preacher Sylvester Graham, a nutrition expert after whom the graham cracker is named.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] The Abernethy biscuit is an adaptation of the plain captain's biscuit or hardtack, with the added ingredients of sugar (for energy), and caraway seeds because of their reputation for having a carminative (flatulence-preventing) effect making them beneficial in digestive disorders.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] The biscuit is between an all butter biscuit and a shortcake, rising through the use of ammonium bicarbonate.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] According to *The Oxford Companion to Food*, a baker at a shop where Abernethy regularly had lunch created the new biscuit when Abernethy suggested it, naming it after him.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] Abernethy biscuits were manufactured by the Aerated Bread Company in the 1870s and 1880s in Adelaide, in the colony of South Australia.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] Abernethy biscuits are still popular in Scotland.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] They are manufactured commercially by Simmers (Edinburgh), The Westray Bakehouse (Orkney Islands), Walls Bakeries (Shetland Islands), and by Stag Bakeries (Isle of Lewis).
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] When British statesman William Gladstone was Vice-President of the Board of Trade in the 1840s, his luncheon consisted of an Abernethy biscuit, brought to him by his wife.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] In the libretto of the comic opera *Princess Toto* written by W.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] Gilbert (first performance 24 June 1876) the king disguises himself as an Abernethy biscuit.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] In Charles Dickens's first novel, *The Pickwick Papers*, the character Mr.
[src:black-pudding/abernethy-biscuit] Solomon Pell is found, "in court, regaling himself, ... , with a cold collation of an Abernethy biscuit and a saveloy".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Living in Hexham, Northumberland, in 1739–1740 Cook and her husband John became embroiled in a feud with a well-connected local landowner, Sir Lancelot Allgood, following an argument over an invoice the Cooks had issued.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Although they were later exonerated, Allgood continued his attack on them, forcing them to leave their inn and move.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Their finances suffered and John was imprisoned for non-payment of debts.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] To earn money, Cook wrote *The New System of Cookery* in 1753, which was reissued as *Professed Cookery* in 1754.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] In the work, in addition to a range of recipes, she included a poem and an "Essay upon the Lady's Art of Cookery".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] This was an attack on Allgood's half-sister Hannah Glasse, who had published a best-selling cookery book, *The Art of Cookery Made Plain and Easy*, in 1747.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Further editions of *Professed Cookery* were published in 1755 and 1760; a revised edition, containing a selection of the recipes from the first edition, was published in 1936.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] In the first two editions of the work, Cook was stated as living in Newcastle upon Tyne; for the 1760 third edition, she was living in lodgings in Holborn, London.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The second and third editions of *Professed Cookery* cover several areas, including a critical analysis of Glasse's work, traditional English recipes and an essay on household management that includes a biography of a friend and Cook's autobiography.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The introduction, written as a poem, accuses Glasse of plagiarism and mocks her capability of being a teacher, as well as poking fun at her illegitimacy.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Little is known about Ann Cook's early life, although she was probably born in the late 1690s and possibly in County Durham.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] According to the autobiographical account she included in her cookery book, she worked as a cook and housekeeper; the historian Madeleine Hope Dodds considers it likely that she went into service aged about twelve.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Ann married John Cook around 1725–1727; he was the licensed tenant of the Black Bull inn in Hexham, Northumberland.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The Black Bull was one of the principal inns of the town and contained assembly rooms for social events.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] It is possible that the Cooks were Roman Catholic.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The couple had at least two daughters—the elder of whom was born in 1728—and three sons.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] In 1739–1740, during the Lent circuit of the assizes, Sir Lancelot Allgood, who held positions of high sheriff and Member of Parliament, sent a message to the Black Bull that the visiting judge and his party wanted six bottles of good French wine, and that John Cook should order them in.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The judge was dissatisfied with the wine and sent a message to Allgood's estate to borrow wine from there; Allgood sent him the bottles as a gift.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] As the original six bottles of wine had been consumed, John charged them to Allgood's account.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] When Allgood and the judge met, they came to the erroneous conclusion that John had charged the judge for the gifted wine.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Allgood publicly accused the landlord of cheating him, and threatened to ruin him, resulting in a feud between the two, partly inflamed by Ann's defence of her husband.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] In late 1745 the Cooks moved from the Black Bull to Morpeth, Northumberland, where they ran the Queen's Head inn on behalf of the landlord, Thomas Pye.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] To secure their position, they entered into a bond of £369 with Pye.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The Cooks did not know that Pye was a cousin of Allgood; in 1746 Allgood accused Mr Cook of being, in Dodds's words "a rebel, a rogue and a villain".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Calling him "a rebel" was an accusation of his being a Jacobite—the Jacobite rising of 1745 still continued and was causing fear in many parts of northern England.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The persecution continued in 1749 when Pye instigated a rumour that because the Cooks were selling their household possessions, they were insolvent and on the verge of abandoning the town.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] In reality they were giving some of their unneeded possessions to their eldest daughter who had recently married and was running an inn with her new husband in Newcastle upon Tyne.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] By this stage the Cooks had paid back £320 of the £369 bond; they sold most of their remaining goods and moved to Newcastle with the intention of setting up a pastrycook shop.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Their creditors followed them for the balance of the bond, and would not allow any terms for an easy settlement; John was taken to a debtors' prison within a month of their arrival in the new town.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] According to Gilly Lehmann, Cook's biographer in the *Oxford Dictionary of National Biography*, it appears that Cook wrote *The New System of Cookery* in order to earn money.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The work was on sale by February 1753; the title page stated the book was "sold by the Author, at her House in the Groat-market" in Newcastle.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The work was republished in 1754 under the title *Professed Cookery*.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] In addition to recipes, the book contained a poem and an "Essay upon the Lady's Art of Cookery".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Both the poem and essay were an attack on Allgood's half-sister, Hannah Glasse, who had published the cookery book *The Art of Cookery Made Plain and Easy* in 1747; Glasse's work was a best-seller and made her one of the best-known writers of the time.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] A second edition of *Professed Cookery* was published in 1755, which added a "Plan of House-Keeping" to the contents.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Cook's address was again given on the title page as a house in the Groat-market.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] A third edition of *Professed Cookery* was published around or after 1760; its title page stated that Cook was a lodger at the house of the cabinet maker Mr Moor, in Fuller's Rents, Holborn, London.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] It is not known what became of Cook after the third edition was published.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] A later edition, published in 1936 by Oxford University Press, comprises extracts of the 1760 printing and was edited by one Regula Burnet, who arranged "A Plan of House-Keeping" into further chapters and also updated the punctuation.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The introduction ("To the reader") is written in the form of a poem, in what Lehmann describes as "appalling doggerel".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Cook warns that Glasse's aim was not to educate, but "To fleece the poor low servants to get wealth / And collect surfeits to destroy all health".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Glasse extensively used other sources in the book: of the 972 recipes in the first edition, at least 342 had been copied or adapted from other works without attribution.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] This plagiarism was typical of the time as the Statute of Anne—the 1709 Act of Parliament dealing with copyright protection—did not protect recipes from copyright infringement.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Cook does not refer to Glasse by name, but mockingly refers to her as "the lady" or "the lady teacher", and as such she ridicules the idea of a lady—of high social class—being in a position to teach cookery to a professional.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Cook knew that Glasse was illegitimate, and refers to this when she rhetorically asks her readers "What Title can be due to broken Glass".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The second edition of *Professed Cookery* includes a chapter of criticism of Glasse's *Art of Cookery*, "An Essay on the Lady's *Art of Cookery*", which covers 66 pages.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The attacks on Glasse were described by Dodds as a "violent onslaught", although much of Cook's criticism about the recipes and treatment of food is warranted, according to the social historian Jennifer Stead.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Stead gives as an example Glasse's recipe for French barley pudding, which calls for one imperial quart (1,100 ml; 38 US fl oz) of cream and one-half pound (230 g) of butter for six handfuls of barley, Cook considers the result would be "a well of oil swimming upon the barley".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Similarly, Glasse's recipe "To Make a Pellow" (pilaf) calls for eighteen pounds (8.2 kg) of meat and one pound (0.45 kg) of rice; Cook thinks this would have the texture of glue, as "whoever gets the rice in their mouths, 'twill stick to their teeth like bird-lime".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Although Glasse ridiculed the expense of ingredients in other cookery books, many of her own recipes are unnecessarily extravagant and wasteful according to Lehmann.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] A supposedly economical recipe for a cabbage (costing 1⁄2d) is, in Stead's words, "dressed with luxury items worth 2s 1d".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The resultant dish would be something no "man, woman or child, hog, sow or dog" would eat, according to Cook.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Glasse's cooking methods are also derided in *Professed Cookery*: the recipe which called for oysters to be larded and roasted on a spit, was mocked, as "the oysters will baste to pieces, and [it is] beyond Art to keep them on the spit".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Glasse's recipe "How to Preserve Cocks-Combs" includes instructions to add vinegar to boiling fat; Cook points out that it "would give a crack like a cannon; so that there would be no need of the chimney sweeping, for the blast would down the soot at once, and destroy the pretty supper-plate".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Stead theorises that Glasse "did not fully understand or appreciate deep frying" as a cooking method, given the errors she makes in the recipes.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] According to the Anglicist Andrew Monnickendam, "Cook's wit and sarcasm produce amusing moments and valid criticism, yet such heavy doses of vitriol eventually tire some readers".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Stead agrees, and says the continued criticism can become tedious, although in places the criticism "has the chill elegance of a rapier thrust through her heart".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Burnet thinks it "interesting and, in some places, amusing".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Lehmann writes that Cook's recipes are more traditional than those provided by Glasse, but it is clear she was also familiar with the French sources used in *The Art of Cookery*, including the recipes of Vincent La Chapelle.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The chapter "A Plan of House-Keeping" takes the form of a narrative of Cook meeting a friend with whom she had lost touch for thirty years.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Although the text does not clarify the point, Burnet considers it likely that this chapter was not written by Cook alone, but by Cook transcribing a friend's part of the story as the two women talked.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Burnet sees two different dispositions behind the descriptions, with the friend being more kind and charitable than Cook, whom Burnet describes as "doubtless a very worthy woman, [who] was by nature litigious and quarrelsome.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] She was never happier than when she was in the middle of a stand-up fight, nor than when she was proving some one else to be in the wrong." Nevertheless, Burnet considers that "Though ...
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Mrs Cook is rather involved, she has a good narrative sense".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] In the chapter, the text describes the stories of the lives of two friends, while interweaving instructions on their approaches and lessons on housekeeping as a domestic servant.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] This includes the best ways to manage servants.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] The instructions include information relating to the management and care of live poultry and how, by doing this properly, one can achieve the optimal flavour from the animal, and ensure the person eating has the best result.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] According to Monnickendam much of the description is "based on cleanliness and respect for the animal's welfare.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Her ideas share many common points with ecological farming of today".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Cook writes that she would rise no later than 6:00 am to look after the poultry—and two hours earlier if there was "an elegant dinner to send up".
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] In the 1936 edition, edited by Regula Burnet, knowledge of Cook's personal history was limited solely to *Professed Cookery*, with no further details known about her.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] When Dodds saw a copy of the 1936 edition, she was working on the history of the Allgood family and was able to identify Cook and her connection to Glasse.
[src:black-pudding/ann-cook-cookery-book-writer] Dodds's research into Cook's background was published in *Archaeologia Aeliana* in 1938.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] The word *pudding* comes from the French *boudin*, originally from the Latin *botellus*, meaning "small sausage".
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Black puddings are often considered to be one of the oldest forms of sausage.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Animals are generally bled at slaughter, and as blood rapidly spoils unless prepared in some way, making a pudding with it is one of the easiest ways of ensuring it does not go to waste.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] While the majority of modern black pudding recipes involve pork blood, this has not always been the case.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Sheep or cow blood was also used, and one 15th-century English recipe used that of a porpoise in a pudding eaten exclusively by the nobility.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Until at least the 19th century, cow or sheep blood was the usual basis for black puddings in Scotland; Jamieson's Scottish dictionary defined "black pudding" as "a pudding made of the blood of a cow or sheep".
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] As a product of the slaughtering process, eating black puddings was historically associated with Martinmas, when the annual slaughter of livestock took place.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] By the 19th century black pudding manufacture was linked with towns known for their large markets for pork, such as Stretford, then in Lancashire, and Cork, Ireland.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] By this time, black puddings were generally omitted from recipe books aimed at urban housewives, as they no longer usually had access to home-killed pork, although recipes continued to appear in Scottish books until the 20th century.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Most traditional recipes from the UK involve stirring the fresh blood, adding fat and some form of rusk, and seasoning, before filling the mixture into a casing and boiling it.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Natural casings of beef intestine were formerly used, though modern commercially made puddings use synthetic cellulose skins, and are usually produced from imported dried blood.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] The relatively limited range of ingredients and use of oats or barley to thicken and absorb the blood is typical of black pudding in comparison to Continental blood sausages.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Despite this, black pudding recipes still show more regional variation across the islands than other sausages, with many butchers having their own individual versions.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Breadcrumbs or flour are sometimes used to supplement the oats or barley, and the proportion and texture of the fat or suet used can also vary widely.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Pennyroyal, marjoram, thyme, and mint are all traditional flavourings: pennyroyal was known as *pudding-yerb* in the North Riding of Yorkshire for its use in black puddings.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Other herbs and spices sometimes used in traditional black puddings include cumin, rue, and parsley.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] While the dish has been known as *black pudding* for centuries, *blak podyngs* having been recorded c.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] 1450, a number of dialect names have also been used for the dish, such as *black pot* (in Somerset), and *bloody pot*.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] It was also found in Yorkshire, where black puddings were flavoured with lemon thyme and savory: Barnsley black puddings were particularly well-known.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] The Stornoway black pudding, made in the Western Isles of Scotland, has been granted Protected Geographical Indicator of Origin status.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] In the wake of this designation, butchers in Bury sought to demonstrate their history of manufacturing and selling the product.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Having been brought there by immigrants, black pudding is now part of the local cuisine of the Canadian provinces of Nova Scotia and Newfoundland and Labrador.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] In Ireland, in addition to the more general type of black pudding, there is a distinct regional variety called drisheen, which is particularly associated with Cork.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Drisheen is usually made from cow's blood, although until the recent past it was often also made with sheep blood, and was sometimes flavoured with tansy.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Sneem Black Pudding is a local variety produced in County Kerry; it has Protected Geographical Indication (PGI) status.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Black pudding can be grilled, fried, baked, or boiled in its skin.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] It can also be eaten cold, as it is cooked in production.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] In parts of north-western England and in the Black Country, it was usual to serve a whole black pudding boiled as a complete meal, with bread or potatoes.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Elsewhere in the UK and Ireland, slices of fried or grilled black pudding are more usually served as part of a traditional full breakfast, a tradition that followed British and Irish emigrants around the world.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Some chip shops, particularly in Scotland and Northern England sell deep-fried, battered black pudding.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Novel culinary uses for black pudding include black pudding ice cream, while perhaps a more conventional modern recipe is using it as an accompaniment to scallops.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Scotch eggs made with black pudding, such as the "Manchester egg", have become common.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Black pudding is a good source of protein; it is low in carbohydrates and high in zinc and iron.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] It has been described as a "superfood" because of these nutritional qualities, although many recipes are also very high in saturated fat and salt.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] Since the 1980s, the World Black Pudding Throwing Championships has been held annually in Ramsbottom, Bury, Greater Manchester.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] The humorous competition invokes the traditional Lancashire – Yorkshire rivalry, with participants throwing the black puddings at piles of Yorkshire puddings.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] It takes place in September, and draws thousands of competitors and spectators.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] In past years, the Bacup Food and Black Pudding Festival has been held in Bacup, Lancashire.
[src:black-pudding/black-pudding] There is an annual European Black Pudding competition held in the Halles de Boudin in Mortagne-au-Perche, Normandy.
